<br>
So here's the question:  Is it better to be overtly leaning in one direction and then try to pass yourself off as fair and balanced or to have more subtle leanings but rely on a more pervasive insinuation of fairness (I know it doesn't make sense right now... it might not later either... but read on).<br>
<br>
What I mean by the pervasive insinuation is this:  In general, people will asceed that Fox News isn't fair nor balanced, but you'd have a much tougher time getting people to make a similar conclusion about news institutions like NBC, ABC, or CBS, even though a similar prejudice is evident on those networks.  Most people don't think to question those organizations to the extent that they would question Fox News.  <br>
<br>
All media will have a bias.  People write the stories, people read the stories to the audiance and add their inflections and emphasis, and editors decide what goes on the air and when. It's impossible not to have bias.  And bias isn't always a bad thing.  However, journalism bias has changed (some say progressed) in the last few decades, to become more subtle.  I think that's one of the reasons why Fox News is such a target for people, aside from their bias and their accuracy, is that it's a throwback to the days of Yellow Journalism to a certain extent.  And it's easy to see. With NBC, CBS, and ABC it's much more difficult to see it, yet it's still there.<br>
<br>
Personally, and we've discussed things on here before, I check at least three or four sources before I begin to find a controversial news story credible.  If they all have different spins on the topic, I'll always doubt the assertion at the center of the story, and rarely feel that it's truly credible.  And 3/4 of my sources will be print, as even though I worked in radio news I don't find electronic media to be too credible to begin with.  They don't have enough time to go into the depths of the story that you do in a newspaper.<br>
<br>
A quick question to end it.  Do you just gravitate towards newspapers or electronic media that furthers and reinforces their own agenda and dismiss the media that provides a counterpoint or do you examine all points of view and come to a conclusion on your own.<br>
<br>
