<br>
When one organization has too much control over the news, be it print, TV or radio or a mixture of the three, they have too much control over what the public finds out. The stories they chose to cover will be the only things covered, whereas if the ownership is spread out, there is a greater chance that various editors/owners will cover more topics. Ommission is probably an innocent sin, but there is also the more sinister implications of cover-ups. <br>
<br>
(And on a side note, the &quot;Clear-channelization&quot; of America has ruined the music industry. You basically hear the same stations in every market playing the same crap in the same pidgeon holed categories from Boston to San Diego. WXRT Chicago is the one notable exception that is left. How can any new talent break in unless they can be cheerfully boxed into a convenient category so clear channel can determine what station to play it on?)<br>
<br>
